t the fore. A social mutation occurred with its division into the ‘White’ British town and the ‘Black’ Indian town.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nAnd the 20<sup>th</sup> century saw Calcutta getting bombed by the Japanese, large scale communal riots and the heartbreak of the partition of India on the dawn of independence. History continued to be unkind with the Naxalites damaging the city’s infrastructure in the 70s and the Indo-Pak war seeing an influx of immigrants that drained the city’s resources. But a decade later, Calcutta began reforming herself to the changing India. Governed by the only communist regime democratically elected, it has seen unsubstantiated growth and today stands as one of the major metropolitan cites of India. It returned to its namesake, Kolkata in 2001 as it cemented its hold on the new century.\r\n<div class="m_5646992537296710409gmail-x_im">\r\n\r\nAs you travel the roads of Kolkata, don’t be overwhelmed by the feeling of having stepped into a history textbook with doodles of modernity on the sides. The city has maintained its artistic artifices that stand proud and tall among the lush greens and the placid water bodies dotting the city. Kolkata has maintained the edge that history gave it in terms of art and literature. It is still the hot bed of furious creative energy and propaganda. The best time to visit would be between September and March. It is during these months that one can truly experience the vivacity and color that is the soul of Bengali Culture.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\nthe National Library  is the largest in the country with a store house of all the publications within the last century. Venture into the mind of Aryabhatta as you visit the Birla Planetorium.\r\n\r\nThe variety of exhibits and celestial modals allow an enriching experience in astronomy.  You could take a mental break and enjoy the fairs and bazaars in the allotted section of the historical Fort William. It is still a military base with arsenal worth competing against, but you’d be lucky if you got the commanding officers permission. Delve into the art archives as the Marble Palace is sure to take your breath away; not only with its exquisite Reubens, Rembrandts, Reynolds and Van Goghs  but also its awe inspiring architecture and its zoo which has an superb collection of some of the rarest and most beautiful birds in the world. But no visit is complete without a visit to the Victoria Memorial: the crown jewel in Kolkata’s crown. EARLY EACH MORNING, THERE ARE GROUPS PRACTICING YOGA, MANY PARTAKING FOR OVER 30 YEAR. AND NEARBY IS THE STATUE OF A DOUR LOOKING QUEEN  WHO NEVER VISITED THE CITY. Sir William Emerson took particular care in its fantastic doric columns and marble finery as its doors open up a world of unparalleled history and art to you. If you are a cricket aficionado, don’t miss out on Eden Gardens! With its revamped and modernized look and enviable seating arrangements, let’s hope you get lucky to catch a tournament while you’re there. Relax at Nicco Park while the kids play around in the various rides and you can revel in the aromas of the rose garden or the traditional Bengali food. Indulge in the flavors of Park Street or spend on the traditional muslin cottons at the various boutique stores. .\r\n\r\nA quick stop at the Writer’s Building and its archives of documents once was the gothic grand house for the junior writers of the East India Company.  Kolkata’s iconic Howrah Bridge has witnessed the mysticism in Kolkata’s art, a satire in her literature, keenness in her science and a diplomatic anarchy in her politics. It is testimony to the salty earthen fragrance that you will carry with you long after you are gone. The goddess and the courtesan, the wife and the lover, the mother and the child, the last and the first- a personification of legacy; she is destiny’s child. Kolkata is a lady who commands a respectful pilgrimage.\r\n<div class="m_5646992537296710409gmail-x_im">\r\n\r\n  But that doesn’t stop Kolkatta and its inhabitants from inviting you with their sparkling eyes and keen intellect.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n[/vc_column_text][distance type="3"][/vc_column][vc_column width="1/3"][distance type="5"][vc_wp_posts number="5"][/vc_column][/vc_row]', 'Delhi', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '9136-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-11-09 10:30:13', '2016-11-09 10:30:13', '', 9136, 'http://localhost/Destinations/2016/11/09/9136-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
